Interview Questions
1) What is a wrapper class in Java, and why do we need it?
-->A wrapper class converts a primitive data type into an object.
    👉 Example:
    int → Integer, char → Character

    Why needed?    
    Collections (like ArrayList) store only objects
    Required for object-oriented features (methods, null handling)
    Used in frameworks, APIs, generics


2) List all wrapper classes in Java for each primitive type.
-->
| Primitive | Wrapper Class |
| --------- | ------------- |
| byte      | Byte          |
| short     | Short         |
| int       | Integer       |
| long      | Long          |
| float     | Float         |
| double    | Double        |
| char      | Character     |
| boolean   | Boolean       |



3) How is a wrapper class different from a primitive type? Give examples.
-->
| Feature     | Primitive   | Wrapper Class |
| ----------- | ----------- | ------------- |
| Type        | Basic value | Object        |
| Memory      | Less        | More          |
| Performance | Faster      | Slower        |
| Null        | Not allowed | Allowed       |



4) Can a wrapper object store null? Give an example.
-->✅ Yes  Integer x = null;


5) What is autoboxing / unboxing in Java? Diff b/w autoboxing and unboxing?
-->Autoboxing: primitive → object
    Unboxing: object → primitive
    Integer a = 10;   // autoboxing
    int b = a;        // unboxing
    
    Difference:    
    Autoboxing = automatic conversion to object
    Unboxing = automatic conversion to primitive



6) Can we perform arithmetic operations directly on wrapper objects? How does it work?
-->✅ Yes, Java automatically unboxes
    Integer a = 10;
    Integer b = 20;
    int c = a + b;  // unboxing happens internally


7) What is the difference between == and .equals() when comparing wrapper objects?
-->== → compares reference (memory address)
    .equals() → compares value
    Integer a = 100;
    Integer b = 100;
    
    System.out.println(a == b);       // true (cached)
    System.out.println(a.equals(b));  // true



8) How does the caching mechanism work for Integer and Boolean?
-->Integer cache range: -128 to 127
    Boolean: only true and false
    Integer a = 127;
    Integer b = 127;
    System.out.println(a == b); // true
    
    Integer x = 128;
    Integer y = 128;
    System.out.println(x == y); // false



9) What happens if you try to unbox a null wrapper object?
-->❌ Throws NullPointerException
    Integer x = null;
    int y = x;  // Exception


10) How does autoboxing affect performance in Java programs?
-->Autoboxing performance impact    
    ⚠️ Slower because:
            Object creation
            Extra memory usage
            Garbage collection overhead
            
    👉 Avoid in loops: Integer sum = 0; // bad for performance



11) Can we declare wrapper objects as final? What happens if we try to change their value?
-->✅ Yes
    final Integer x = 10;

    ❌ You cannot reassign:
          x = 20; // error
    But note:
      Wrapper objects are immutable
      Any change creates a new object


12) Can autoboxing occur when passing arguments to a method? Give an example.
-->✅ Yes
      void display(Integer x) {
          System.out.println(x);
      }
      
      display(10); // autoboxing happens



13) What is the difference between Integer.parseInt() and Integer.valueOf()?
-->
| Method       | Return Type      |
| ------------ | ---------------- |
| `parseInt()` | int (primitive)  |
| `valueOf()`  | Integer (object) |

int a = Integer.parseInt("10");
Integer b = Integer.valueOf("10");



14) What is the behavior of null in wrapper comparisons?
-->Integer a = null;
    Integer b = 10;
    
    System.out.println(a == b); // false
    System.out.println(a.equals(b)); // NullPointerException
    
    👉 Always check null before .equals()


15) Can wrapper objects be synchronized for thread safety?
-->⚠️ Technically yes, but not recommended
    
    Integer x = 10;
    synchronized(x) {
        // unsafe due to caching
    }
    
    👉 Reason:  Cached objects may be shared → leads to unexpected behavior



16) Are wrapper objects immutable? How does Java handle immutability for wrappers?
-->✅ Yes
    Integer a = 10;
    a = a + 5; // new object created
    
    👉 Java ensures immutability by:
            Making class final
            No setters
            Value cannot change once created
